Apr 25 2009 	Excellent base for San Francisco	My husband and I stayed here for three nights as part of as a wider trip around California in March/April. We paid an average of $75 plus tax per night for a standard double room. For San Francisco we felt this was excellent value. The room although not large or particularly stylish was of an adequate size, and clean and comfortable. The bathroom was a good size and included a tub as well as a shower (ie the shower was in the tub). The location was excellent – just a few steps from China Town. It was really easy to get around and we felt safe in the area. After reading other comments on this site, we specifically requested a room away from the lift shaft and didn’t have any problems with noise. Wi-fi is available but there is a daily charge for this so we found it better value to go to a local cafe with free wi-fi instead.No breakfast was provided but coffee was available in the lobby throughout the day. There are lots of cafes etc nearby so finding somewhere for breakfast wasn’t a problem. I’d definitely recommend this as a clean, comfortable and good value base for exploring San Francisco.	
Apr 22 2009 	You Get What You Pay For	I will preface this review by saying that I was looking for the most inexpensive way to stay in a major American city- San Francisco. In this one particular case, after having may successful trips with the advise of Trip Advisor, I was let down by the reviews on The Baldwin Hotel in San Francisco. Suffice it to say, this experience was mostly my own fault in the making. I have learned that indeed, you &quot;get what you pay for&quot;- especially in a large city such as San Fran.Positives: The Baldwin was one of the most inexpensive locales that I found in San Fran. The staff was very friendly and tried to be as accomodating as possible. The rooms were clean- if a bit spare.Negatives: Probably one of the worst nights I have spent in a hotel. The room was located on the 7th floor accessable by a small elevator (which had been mentioned in a previous review). I arrived in San Francisco in the middle of a &quot;heat wave&quot; (which is rare from what the locals tell me) with temps in the 90's. 1) The room had no air conditioning and has only a small water-radiator for heat- which was NOT needed!! The only relief was to open a window (without insect screens) and an overhead fan. As mentioned previously, the room was small. No rooms with King/Queen beds were available, so had two twin beds. 2) The advertised Wifi available is through a company located in -- Oregon-- the Wifi was sporadic at best, with the signal being lost constantly- also a charge of appox. $20 for three days use. 3) Water pressure in the shower/tube was dribbling (very weak) with little hot water available at around 7:30 AM.  3) The noise was the most agonizing factor of my entire one night's stay. My room, on the 7th floor, was located on the side of the building facing an alley-way- the only view was of the building next door (again mentioned in a previous review of this property). All During the night, traffic noise was terrible with the &quot;back-up beeping&quot; of serivce vehicles throughout the night- at one point, when trying to go to sleep apox. 10:30 PM there was about 10 minutes of glass breaking and beeping and the noise of a dumpster truck dumping several containers in the alley- imagine listening to this through an open window. I stayed for one night- I had made the reservations pre-paid through one of the major travel internet sites and, after talking with two hotel clerks and two representatives of this major travel site, I was refused even a partial refund for my booked 4 nights stay- the major travel site did give a $50 certificate for future use as an attempt for an apology.So, the moral of this story is: if you are trying to do your travel &quot;on the cheap&quot;- beware- even with good to moderate reviews on Trip Advisor- one paradise is another person's misery.	
